From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|berye|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|beriġe}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*bazją}}<ref>Marlies Philippa et al., eds., ''Etymologisch Woordenboek van het Nederlands'', A-Z, s.v. “bes” (Amsterdam UP, 3 Dec. 2009): <http://www.etymologie.nl>.</ref> (compare {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Beere|lang=de}}, Danish {{term|bær|lang=da}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*bʰes-||to blow, chew, rub}} (compare Tocharian B {{term|pās-||to whisper|lang=xtb}}, {{etyl|sq|-}} {{term|fshij||to sweep, wipe|lang=sq}}, Ancient Greek {{term|ψάω||I rub|tr=psaō|lang=grc}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term|बभस्ति||he chews, devours|tr=bábhasti|lang=sa}})<ref>J.P. Mallory & D.Q. Adams, eds., ''Encyclopedia of Indo-European Culture'', s.vv. “blow”, “rub” (London: Fitzroy Dearborn, 1997), pp. 72, 490.</ref>. For the semantic development, compare {{etyl|cu|-}} {{term|гроуша||pear|tr=gruša|lang=cu}}, from {{term|гроушити|tr=grušiti||to break, destroy|lang=cu}}; {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|pirum||pear|lang=la}}, from {{term/t|ine-pro|*peis-||to stick, pound}}.<ref>Vladimir Orel, ''A Handbook of Germanic Etymology'', s.v. “*ƀazjan” (Leiden: Brill, 2003), 40.</ref>

